TY  - JOUR
T1  - Market Comparison Earnings and the Bidding-up of Executive Cash Compensation: Evidence From The United Kingdom
AU  - Ezzamel, Mahmoud
AU  - Watson, Robert
Y1  - 1998/04/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/257104
DO  - 10.5465/257104
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 221
EP  - 231
VL  - 41
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We argue that compensation committees will pay executives at least at the going rate and that deviations from that rate will influence subsequent pay. In a sample of large U.K. companies, we estimated whether asymmetric responses to pay anomalies explained executive pay. All three of our pay anomaly measures were statistically related to subsequent pay. Moreover, there was significant nonlinear adjustment toward the going rate for underpaid executives.
AB  - We argue that compensation committees will pay executives at least at the going rate and that deviations from that rate will influence subsequent pay. In a sample of large U.K. companies, we estimated whether asymmetric responses to pay anomalies explained executive pay. All three of our pay anomaly measures were statistically related to subsequent pay. Moreover, there was significant nonlinear adjustment toward the going rate for underpaid executives.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/257104
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/257104
Y2  - 2026/04/24
